04806nam a22007575i 9780231541282DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)952043281  a(OCoLC)984686829  a97802315412827 a10.7312/palm175162doi  a(DE-B1597)473077  a(OCoLC)945735471  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0340002bisacsh04a9012231 aPalmeri, Frank, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aState of Nature, Stages of Society :bEnlightenment Conjectural History and Modern Social Discourse /cFrank Palmeri. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in Political Thought / Political History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Conjectural History, the Form and Its Afterlife -- t1. Conjectural History: The Enlightenment Form -- t2. Political Economy and the Question of Progress -- t3. Comte, Spencer, and the Science of Society -- t4. The Origins of Culture and of Anthropology -- t5. Darwin, Nietzsche, and the Prehistory of the Human -- t6. The Social Psychology of Religion -- t7. Novels as Conjectural Histories -- tConclusion: Conjecturalism Now -- tAppendix 1. Enlightenment Conjectural Histories -- tAppendix 2. Hegel, History, and Conjecture -- tAppendix 3. Were Conjectural Histories Racist? -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrank Palmeri sees the conjectural histories of Rousseau, Hume, Herder, and other Enlightenment philosophers as a template for the development of the social sciences in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Without documents or memorials, these thinkers, he argues, employed conjecture to formulate a naturalistic account of society's commercial and secular progression. Palmeri finds evidence of speculative frameworks in the political economy of Malthus, Martineau, Mill, and Marx. He traces the influence of speculative thought in the development of anthropology and ethnography in the 1860s, the foundational sociology of Comte and Spencer, and the sociology of religion pioneered by Weber, Durkheim, and Freud. Conjectural histories reveal a surprising ambivalence toward progress, modernity, and secularization among leading thinkers of the time, an attitude that affected texts as varied as Darwin's Descent of Man, Nietzsche's Genealogy of Morality, and the novels of Walter Scott, George Eliot, and H.G. Wells. Establishing the critical value of conjectural thinking in the study of modern forms of knowledge, Palmeri concludes his investigation with its return in the work of Foucault and in recent histories on early religion, political organization, and material life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEnlightenment. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aProgressxPhilosophy. 0aSocial historyxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2016z9783110485301oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/palm1751640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231541282423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231541282.jpg  a978-3-11-063857-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE